english:
  title: Inscriptions on Four Ink Paintings of Bamboo for Scholar Jeong Haksa Yi An
  author: Lee Kyubo
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Dew Bamboo

    Solitary and austere, hard is the bamboo's way of life.
    Yet heaven takes pity and anoints it with dew.
    Accept this kindness from above—
    When snow comes, do not fear.

    Wind Bamboo

    What makes you precious?
    Only this: your joints stand straight and true.
    That you bow and sway, never holding firm—
    The wind commands it so.
    Yet your inner nature is empty space;
    Who then can truly shake you?

    Old Bamboo

    Better to grow old and break than surrender your integrity.
    Even jade may shatter, yet its straightness endures.
    Your great leaves do not fall—
    They still call forth the clear wind's whisper.

    Young Bamboo

    Breaking through the earth to rise,
    Wrapped in silken skin like brocade—
    Who plucked your tender shoot so high?
    Beautiful, your spiraling form!
    Yes, you might grow to pierce the sky itself,
    But remember: the tallest trees stand closest to the edge of ruin.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: This work comprises four separate inscriptions (贊), each praising a different representation of bamboo—dew-covered, wind-tossed, aged, and newly sprouted. Through these four perspectives, Li Kyubo explores virtue, resilience, and the proper measure of growth.
  - key: ''
    value: Bamboo held deep symbolic meaning in East Asian literati culture, representing integrity, flexibility, and moral constancy. These inscriptions engage with that tradition while offering philosophical reflection on different stages of life and cultivation.
